					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/adam-smascher" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(587467); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=587467&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610226079" alt="Adam Smascher" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=587467)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/adam-smascher" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(587467); return false;" >Adam Smascher</a></span> <span class="odate time_1483269936 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">01 Jan 2017 11:25</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2718634">
									

<p>Gonna pick up about where I left off in chat.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The products are ready. She's not. [&#8230;] The products are ready.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I think the paragraph where she ties off her arm to shoot up could be tightened up. We don't need the detailed step-by-step process - everyone knows how that goes. Could just tell us she prepares the site and the reader will fill it in.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>It screeches in response; the thick dark fluid inside</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Comma between &quot;thick&quot; and &quot;dark.&quot; Use of &quot;fluid&quot; twice in this paragraph stands out to me, because the first time it's used to refer to an actual liquid, and then to describe an action. Not wrong at all, but second use is a bit unnecessary, as just describing the movement as practiced will suffice and call to mind all the same things. Similar thing with, &quot;She shakes the syringe rapidly to reduce the gorilla back into a thick scarlet sludge.&quot; Already told us the fluid was thick, and sludge is thick, so &quot;thick sludge&quot; is doubly redundant. So as to not have to point out each individual instance, because I'm lazy and do not wish to build a wall that I make Recent Posts pay for, I'll just say that your descriptions can be redundant or more detailed than necessary.</p>
<p>Pretty sure 30 tons is a gross underestimation of how much a freight train is going to weigh. Quick Google search confirms this. Engine cars alone can weigh hundreds of tons, and with cargo you can be talking thousands.</p>
<p>All in all, this isn't my jam. I agree with Roget, that the main character has far too easy a time of something we're told throughout is extremely hard. It reads like a cheesy anime fight, where the characters aren't so much fighting or outsmarting each other as asspulling secret techniques and powers, and that just doesn't do anything for me. Not much of a fan of urban fantasy style things, either, but that's personal taste and not a criticism.</p>

							</div>

								
					
